\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
(Dis)Inflation Targeting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Part
Models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The preferences of the government are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z_{t}=\frac{a}{2}\left(\pi_{t}\right)^{2}-b_{t}(\pi_{t}-\pi_{t}^{e})
\]

\end_inset

and expectations formation are as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{t}\leq\pi_{t}^{e}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{t+1}^{e}=\max\left\{ \gamma\pi_{t},\pi_{t+1}^{\ast}\right\} $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{t+1}^{\ast}$
\end_inset

 is the announced inflation target at 
\begin_inset Formula $t+1$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=0$
\end_inset

 we have the Barro-Gordon case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{t}>\pi_{t}^{e}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{t+1}^{e}=\frac{\bar{b}}{a}$
\end_inset

 the discretionary outcome (
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{b}$
\end_inset

 is the expected 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{t+1})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Case 1: Disinflation follow the threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{t+1}^{\ast}=\gamma\pi_{t}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
IN this case the discounted value for the government is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{0}=\sum_{t=0}^{\infty}\beta^{t}\left[\frac{a}{2}\left(\gamma^{t}\frac{b}{a}\right)^{2}\right]=\sum_{t=0}^{\infty}\beta^{t}\left[\frac{b^{2}}{2a}\gamma^{2t}\right]=\frac{b^{2}}{2a}\frac{1}{1-\beta\gamma^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

and starting form any arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $t=s$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{s}=\sum_{t=0}^{\infty}\beta^{s}\left[\frac{a}{2}\left(\gamma^{s+t}\frac{b}{a}\right)^{2}\right]=\sum_{t=0}^{\infty}\beta^{s}\left[\frac{b^{2}}{2a}\gamma^{2(s+t)}\right]=\frac{b^{2}}{2a}\gamma^{2(s)}\frac{1}{1-\beta\gamma^{2}}=\gamma^{2(s)}V_{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is it whorty to deviate? the value in case the government deviates is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
V_{d,s} & =\frac{a}{2}\left(\frac{b}{a}\right)^{2}-b_{t}(\frac{b}{a}-\gamma^{s}\frac{b}{a})+\beta V_{0}\\
 & =\frac{b^{2}}{2a}-\frac{b^{2}}{a}(1-\gamma^{s})+\beta V_{0}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

then it is optimal to deviate if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{b^{2}}{2a}-\frac{b^{2}}{a}(1-\gamma^{s})+\beta V_{0} & \leq\gamma^{2(s)}V_{0}\\
\frac{b^{2}}{2a}-\frac{b^{2}}{a}(1-\gamma^{s}) & \leq\left(\gamma^{2(s)}-\beta\right)V_{0}\\
\frac{\frac{b^{2}}{a}\left(\gamma^{s}-\frac{1}{2}\right)}{\left(\beta-\gamma^{2(s)}\right)} & \leq V_{0}\\
\frac{\left(2\gamma^{s}-1\right)}{\left(\beta-\gamma^{2(s)}\right)} & \leq\frac{1}{1-\beta\gamma^{2}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=0$
\end_inset

 we recover the Barro-Gordon case where zero inflation is not sustainable
 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\left(-1\right)}{\left(\beta\right)}\leq1
\]

\end_inset

holds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\infty$
\end_inset

 we have 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{b^{2}}{2a}-\frac{b^{2}}{a}+\beta V_{0} & \leq0\\
V_{0} & \leq\frac{1}{\beta}\frac{b^{2}}{2a}\\
\frac{b^{2}}{2a}\frac{1}{1-\beta\gamma^{2}} & \leq\frac{1}{\beta}\frac{b^{2}}{2a}\\
\gamma^{2} & \leq\frac{1}{\beta}-1
\end{align*}

\end_inset

this sets a lower bound on 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 So to have no incentives to deviate at the limit it has to be that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\gamma^{2} & \geq\frac{1}{\beta}-1\\
\gamma & \geq\left(\frac{1}{\beta}-1\right)^{1/2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Going back to the previous condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{b^{2}}{2a}-\frac{b^{2}}{a}(1-\gamma^{s}) & \leq\left(\gamma^{2(s)}-\beta\right)V_{0}\\
-\frac{1}{2}\frac{b^{2}}{a} & \leq\left(\gamma^{2(s)}-\beta\right)V_{0}-\frac{b^{2}}{a}\gamma^{s}\\
-\frac{1}{2} & \leq\left(\gamma^{2(s)}-\beta\right)\frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{1-\beta\gamma^{2}}-\gamma^{s}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

is there a 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 for which this condition is not satisfied for any 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

? In this case we would be able to implement the efficient allocation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Yes! There are values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 for which the condition above is never satisifed for any 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and consequently 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=0$
\end_inset

 can be implemented in the long run.
 See the numerical solutions in the matlab file test.m
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The minimum level of inflation achievable with 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=0$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi^{BG}=\frac{1-\beta}{1+\beta}\frac{b}{a}
\]

\end_inset

and the value is then given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V^{BG}=\frac{1}{2}\frac{b^{2}}{a}\frac{1-\beta}{\left(1+\beta\right)^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

so the Barro Gordon porvides higher welfare ex-ante than our case with 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma>0$
\end_inset

.
 Down the road for 
\begin_inset Formula $s>1$
\end_inset

 then the welfare in our case is greater and at the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $s\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 the loss in our case is zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So the plan is not dinamically consistent without the constraint of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
New setup
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Expectations 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{t+1}^{e}=\gamma_{t}\pi_{t}+(1-\gamma_{t})\pi_{t+1}^{a}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
IS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{t}=b(\pi_{t}-\pi_{t}^{e})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
updating exp
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma_{t+1}=(1-\theta)\gamma_{t}+\theta(\pi_{t+1}-\pi_{t+1}^{a})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Organizational equilibrium for inflation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Adaptative expectations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The preferences of the government are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z_{t}=\frac{a}{2}\left(\pi_{t}\right)^{2}-b_{t}(\pi_{t}-\pi_{t}^{e})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and expectations are adaptative 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{t+1}^{e}=\pi_{t}
\]

\end_inset

in this case the markov equilibrium has the property that the expectations
 are rational.
 Any stationary equilibrium would have that the adaptative expectations
 are rational.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this case we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{t}^{e}$
\end_inset

 becomes a state of the economy.
 The action of the central bank can be defined as the inflation surprise
 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{t}=\pi_{t}-\pi_{t}^{e}
\]

\end_inset

 and the payoff function is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z_{t}(\pi_{t}^{e},s_{t})=\frac{a}{2}\left(s_{t}+\pi_{t}^{e}\right)^{2}-b_{t}(s_{t})
\]

\end_inset

that can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z_{t}(\pi_{t}^{e},s_{t})=\frac{a}{2}\left(s_{t}\right)^{2}+a\left(s_{t}\pi_{t}^{e}\right)+\frac{a}{2}\left(\pi_{t}^{e}\right)^{2}-b_{t}(s_{t})
\]

\end_inset

for now we ignore the second term 
\begin_inset Formula $a\left(s_{t}\pi_{t}^{e}\right)\approx0$
\end_inset

 to satisfy the separability requirement.
 Alternatively a linear approximation of that term could be used where the
 constants are adjusted ex-post once the solution is found (iterating here
 would give us an approximation of the solution).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So the instantanous payoff is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z_{t}(\pi_{t}^{e},s_{t})=\frac{a}{2}\left(s_{t}\right)^{2}+\frac{a}{2}\left(\pi_{t}^{e}\right)^{2}-b_{t}(s_{t})
\]

\end_inset

and consequently the lifetime payoff at 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
v\left(\pi_{t}^{e},\left\{ s_{t}\right\} _{t=0}^{\infty}\right) & =\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\beta^{j}z_{t}(\pi_{t+j}^{e},s_{t+j})\\
 & =\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\beta^{j}\left(\frac{a}{2}\left(s_{t+j}\right)^{2}+\frac{a}{2}\left(\pi_{t+j}^{e}\right)^{2}-b_{t}(s_{t+j})\right)\\
 & =\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\beta^{j}\left(\frac{a}{2}\left(s_{t+j}\right)^{2}+\frac{a}{2}\left(\pi_{t+j-1}\right)^{2}-b_{t}(s_{t+j})\right)\\
 & =\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\beta^{j}\left(\frac{a}{2}\left(s_{t+j}\right)^{2}+\frac{a}{2}\left(\pi_{t}^{e}+\sum_{i=0}^{j}s_{t+i}\right)^{2}-b_{t}(s_{t+j})\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In this case we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{t}^{e}$
\end_inset

 becomes a state of the economy.
 The action of the central bank can be defined as the inflation surprise
 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{t}=\pi_{t}/\pi_{t}^{e}
\]

\end_inset

 and the payoff function is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z_{t}(\pi_{t}^{e},s_{t})=\frac{a}{2}\left(s_{t}\pi_{t}^{e}\right)^{2}-\frac{1}{\pi_{t}^{e}}b_{t}(s_{t}-1)
\]

\end_inset

that can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z_{t}(\pi_{t}^{e},s_{t})=\frac{a}{2}\left(s_{t}\right)^{2}\left(\pi_{t}^{e}\right)^{2}-\frac{1}{\pi_{t}^{e}}b_{t}(s_{t}-1)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Expectations set by the target
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The preferences of the government are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z_{t}=\frac{a}{2}\left(\pi_{t}\right)^{2}-b_{t}(\pi_{t}-\pi_{t}^{e})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and expectations are set to the target 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pi_{t+1}^{e} & =\begin{cases}
\pi_{t}^{\ast} & \text{if }\pi_{t}=\pi_{t-1}^{\ast}\\
\pi_{t} & \text{else}
\end{cases}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{t}^{\ast}$
\end_inset

 is the target announced at 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 for inflation at 
\begin_inset Formula $t+1$
\end_inset

.
 In this case we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{t}^{e}$
\end_inset

 becomes a state of the economy.
 The other action of the central bank is inflation 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{t}$
\end_inset

, so the action vector is 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}=\{\pi_{t},\pi_{t}^{\ast}\}$
\end_inset

 where the current state is 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{0}^{e}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The payoff function is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z(\pi_{t}^{e},s_{t})=\frac{a}{2}\left(\pi_{t}\right)^{2}-b_{t}(\pi_{t}-\pi_{t}^{e})
\]

\end_inset

and consequently the lifetime payoff at 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
v\left(\pi_{0}^{e},\left\{ s_{t}\right\} _{t=0}^{\infty}\right) & =\sum_{t=0}^{\infty}\beta^{t}z(\pi_{t}^{e},s_{t})\\
 & =\sum_{t=0}^{\infty}\beta^{t}\left(\frac{a}{2}\left(\pi_{t}\right)^{2}-b_{t}(\pi_{t}-\pi_{t-1}^{\ast})\right)\\
 & =\frac{a}{2}\left(\pi_{0}\right)^{2}-b_{t}(\pi_{0}-\pi_{0}^{e})+\sum_{t=1}^{\infty}\beta^{t}\left(\frac{a}{2}\left(\pi_{t}\right)^{2}-b_{t}(\pi_{t}-\pi_{t-1}^{\ast})\right)\\
 & =b_{0}\pi_{0}^{e}+\frac{a}{2}\left(\pi_{0}\right)^{2}-b_{t}(\pi_{0})+\beta b_{1}\pi_{0}^{\ast}+\sum_{t=1}^{\infty}\beta^{t}\left(\frac{a}{2}\left(\pi_{t}\right)^{2}-b_{t}(\pi_{t})\right)+\sum_{t=1}^{\infty}\beta^{t}b_{t+1}(\pi_{t}^{\ast})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so we have that the separability condition is satisfied as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v\left(\pi_{0}^{e},\left\{ s_{t}\right\} _{t=0}^{\infty}\right)=b_{0}\pi_{0}^{e}+V\left(\left\{ s_{t}\right\} _{t=0}^{\infty}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(\left\{ s_{t}\right\} _{t=0}^{\infty}\right)=\frac{a}{2}\left(\pi_{0}\right)^{2}-b_{t}(\pi_{0})+\beta b_{1}\pi_{0}^{\ast}+\sum_{t=1}^{\infty}\beta^{t}\left(\frac{a}{2}\left(\pi_{t}\right)^{2}-b_{t}(\pi_{t})\right)+\sum_{t=1}^{\infty}\beta^{t}b_{t+1}(\pi_{t}^{\ast})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Expectations averaging actual inflation and the target.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The preferences of the government are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z_{t}=\frac{a}{2}\left(\pi_{t}\right)^{2}-b_{t}(\pi_{t}-\pi_{t}^{e})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and expectations are set be an average of current inflation and the target
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pi_{t+1}^{e} & =\gamma\pi_{t}+(1-\gamma)\pi_{t}^{\ast}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{t}^{\ast}$
\end_inset

 is the target announced at 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 for inflation at 
\begin_inset Formula $t+1$
\end_inset

.
 In this case we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{t}^{e}$
\end_inset

 becomes a state of the economy.
 The other action of the central bank is inflation 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{t}$
\end_inset

, so the action vector is 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}=\{\pi_{t},\pi_{t}^{\ast}\}$
\end_inset

 where the current state is 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{0}^{e}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This has the problem that the planner can always fool agents by having a
 very low target to guarantee it can always surprise agents 
\end_layout

